  <lesson>
    <title>2. Coping: how to do your language-learning IN the language</title>
    <designnote>This particular lesson is offered right from the start,			because it is most effective for learners to learn the language			THROUGH the language. By giving them the crucial phrases for this			early on, we aim to encourage doing this as much as possible from the			getgo, instead of dropping back to English. Learners of course			naturally drop back to English, but so do speakers, since it is the			language they have used with non-speakers for years. A successful			learner has to overcome not only their own lifelong habits of using			English, but also has to find polite, respectful ways of turning the			conversation from English back to Mi'gmaq wherever reasonably			possible. These phrases are one of the key ways they can do this.</designnote>
    <note>@20120731-JV-2redux.wav is the complete and revised version of			all of this section. There is also			@20120723-JW-RM-1thru25.wav@0:39.5-1:54, as an early draft that would			need a redo @0:44, but is otherwise good for voice variation. Note			also that there are revised versions of the "fill in the blank"			forms, as actual blank-fillers are much better.</note>
    <timesig>@20120731-JV-2redux.wav</timesig>
    <explnote>When you learn a new language, you want to stay speaking		in the language as much as possible:		the more your mind goes back to English, the slower you will learn.		One great trick to keep the conversation solidly in Mig'maq---even		when you're not following everything---		is to learn how to ask your major questions ABOUT the langauge IN the		language.		Here we give the first of a series of phrases that you can use to help		stay in the game, no matter what....</explnote>
    <dialog>
      <line>
        <migmaq>Ge' nnu'-gluli.</migmaq>
        <english>Please speak to me in Native.</english>
        <soundfile>S1U1/2_Coping/01-GeNnuGluliCLP</soundfile>
      </line>
      <line>
        <migmaq>Tali-ulm'tu'n 'nnuigtug gluli.</migmaq>
        <english>Would you be so kind as to talk to me in Native?</english>
        <soundfile>S1U1/2_Coping/02-TaliUlmtunNnuigtugGluliCLP</soundfile>
      </line>
    </dialog>
